</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Almost all neoplasms of the pancreas are derived from pancreatic epithelial components, including the most common pancreatic mass, primary pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC). Nonepithelial neoplasms comprise only 1%–2% of all pancreatic neoplasms. Although some may arise directly from intrapancreatic elements, many originate from mesenchymal, hematopoietic, or neural elements in the retroperitoneal peripancreatic space and grow into the pancreas. Once these tumors reach a certain size, it can be challenging to identify their origin. Because these manifest at imaging as intrapancreatic masses, awareness of the existence and characteristic features of these nonepithelial neoplasms is crucial for the practicing radiologist in differentiating these tumors from primary epithelial pancreatic tumors, an important distinction given the vastly different management and prognosis. In part 1 of this article, the authors reviewed benign nonepithelial neoplasms of the pancreas. This article focuses on malignant nonepithelial neoplasms and those of uncertain malignant potential that can be seen in the pancreas. The most common malignant or potentially malignant nonepithelial pancreatic tumors are of mesenchymal origin and include soft-tissue sarcomas, solitary fibrous tumor, and inflammatory myofibroblastic tumor. These tumors commonly manifest as large heterogeneous masses, often containing areas of necrosis and hemorrhage. The clinical features associated with these tumors and the imaging characteristics including enhancement patterns and the presence of fat or calcification help distinguish these tumors from PDAC. Hematopoietic tumors, including lymphoma and extramedullary plasmacytoma, can manifest as isolated pancreatic involvement or secondarily involve the pancreas as widespread disease. Hyperenhancing paragangliomas or hypervascular metastatic disease can mimic primary pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors or vascular anomalies.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170201">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170201">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig1a.jpeg" height="1323" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Leiomyosarcoma incidentally discovered in an otherwise healthy 42-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-demarcated firm white-yellow mass (arrow) surrounded by normal lobulated pancreatic parenchyma (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-demarcated mass composed of spindle cells in a storiform pattern (arrow) within normal pancreatic acini (<b>*</b>). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a well-defined hypoechoic mass (arrow) along the superior margin of the relatively hyperechoic pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a homogeneously hypointense mass (arrow) centered on the body of the pancreas, compared with the normally hyperintense pancreatic tissue (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial MR image obtained after contrast material administration during the blood pool phase shows enhancement of the periphery of the mass with central hypoenhancement (arrow), suggestive of central necrosis. <b>*</b> = normal pancreatic enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig1b.jpeg" height="1323" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Leiomyosarcoma incidentally discovered in an otherwise healthy 42-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-demarcated firm white-yellow mass (arrow) surrounded by normal lobulated pancreatic parenchyma (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-demarcated mass composed of spindle cells in a storiform pattern (arrow) within normal pancreatic acini (<b>*</b>). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a well-defined hypoechoic mass (arrow) along the superior margin of the relatively hyperechoic pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a homogeneously hypointense mass (arrow) centered on the body of the pancreas, compared with the normally hyperintense pancreatic tissue (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial MR image obtained after contrast material administration during the blood pool phase shows enhancement of the periphery of the mass with central hypoenhancement (arrow), suggestive of central necrosis. <b>*</b> = normal pancreatic enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig1c.jpeg" height="1233" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Leiomyosarcoma incidentally discovered in an otherwise healthy 42-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-demarcated firm white-yellow mass (arrow) surrounded by normal lobulated pancreatic parenchyma (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-demarcated mass composed of spindle cells in a storiform pattern (arrow) within normal pancreatic acini (<b>*</b>). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a well-defined hypoechoic mass (arrow) along the superior margin of the relatively hyperechoic pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a homogeneously hypointense mass (arrow) centered on the body of the pancreas, compared with the normally hyperintense pancreatic tissue (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial MR image obtained after contrast material administration during the blood pool phase shows enhancement of the periphery of the mass with central hypoenhancement (arrow), suggestive of central necrosis. <b>*</b> = normal pancreatic enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig1d.jpeg" height="1234" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Leiomyosarcoma incidentally discovered in an otherwise healthy 42-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-demarcated firm white-yellow mass (arrow) surrounded by normal lobulated pancreatic parenchyma (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-demarcated mass composed of spindle cells in a storiform pattern (arrow) within normal pancreatic acini (<b>*</b>). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a well-defined hypoechoic mass (arrow) along the superior margin of the relatively hyperechoic pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a homogeneously hypointense mass (arrow) centered on the body of the pancreas, compared with the normally hyperintense pancreatic tissue (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial MR image obtained after contrast material administration during the blood pool phase shows enhancement of the periphery of the mass with central hypoenhancement (arrow), suggestive of central necrosis. <b>*</b> = normal pancreatic enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig1e.jpeg" height="1234" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Leiomyosarcoma incidentally discovered in an otherwise healthy 42-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-demarcated firm white-yellow mass (arrow) surrounded by normal lobulated pancreatic parenchyma (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-demarcated mass composed of spindle cells in a storiform pattern (arrow) within normal pancreatic acini (<b>*</b>). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c)</b> Transverse gray-scale ultrasonographic (US) image in the midline abdomen shows a well-defined hypoechoic mass (arrow) along the superior margin of the relatively hyperechoic pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a homogeneously hypointense mass (arrow) centered on the body of the pancreas, compared with the normally hyperintense pancreatic tissue (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial MR image obtained after contrast material administration during the blood pool phase shows enhancement of the periphery of the mass with central hypoenhancement (arrow), suggestive of central necrosis. <b>*</b> = normal pancreatic enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig2a.jpeg" height="1235" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Leiomyosarcoma in a 43-year-old woman with nausea, vomiting, and abdominal bloating. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows peripheral enhancement of a large heterogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) with central areas of relatively diminished enhancement (curved arrow). <b>*</b> = normal pancreas. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image <b>(b)</b> and thick-slab heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram <b>(c)</b> show central areas of nonenhancing (curved arrow in <b>b</b>) and T2 hyperintense (curved arrow in <b>c</b>) necrosis. Note the normal enhancement and T2 signal intensity of the normal pancreas (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) without significant dilatation of the common bile duct (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) or pancreatic duct (straight arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig2b.jpeg" height="1235" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Leiomyosarcoma in a 43-year-old woman with nausea, vomiting, and abdominal bloating. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows peripheral enhancement of a large heterogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) with central areas of relatively diminished enhancement (curved arrow). <b>*</b> = normal pancreas. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image <b>(b)</b> and thick-slab heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram <b>(c)</b> show central areas of nonenhancing (curved arrow in <b>b</b>) and T2 hyperintense (curved arrow in <b>c</b>) necrosis. Note the normal enhancement and T2 signal intensity of the normal pancreas (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) without significant dilatation of the common bile duct (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) or pancreatic duct (straight arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig2c.jpeg" height="1235" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Leiomyosarcoma in a 43-year-old woman with nausea, vomiting, and abdominal bloating. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows peripheral enhancement of a large heterogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) with central areas of relatively diminished enhancement (curved arrow). <b>*</b> = normal pancreas. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image <b>(b)</b> and thick-slab heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram <b>(c)</b> show central areas of nonenhancing (curved arrow in <b>b</b>) and T2 hyperintense (curved arrow in <b>c</b>) necrosis. Note the normal enhancement and T2 signal intensity of the normal pancreas (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) without significant dilatation of the common bile duct (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) or pancreatic duct (straight arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig3a.jpeg" height="1477" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Liposarcoma in a 46-year-old man with left upper quadrant and epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic atypical adipocytes and lipoblasts with hyperchromatic indented nuclei (straight arrow) and atypical spindle cells (curved arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the nuclei are positive for MDM2 (arrow). (MDM2 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a solid and cystic mass (arrow) in the posterior pancreatic body (arrowhead) without visible fat. <b>(d)</b> Fused FDG PET/CT image at the same level shows FDG avidity in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig3b.jpeg" height="1477" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Liposarcoma in a 46-year-old man with left upper quadrant and epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic atypical adipocytes and lipoblasts with hyperchromatic indented nuclei (straight arrow) and atypical spindle cells (curved arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the nuclei are positive for MDM2 (arrow). (MDM2 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a solid and cystic mass (arrow) in the posterior pancreatic body (arrowhead) without visible fat. <b>(d)</b> Fused FDG PET/CT image at the same level shows FDG avidity in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig3c.jpeg" height="1377" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Liposarcoma in a 46-year-old man with left upper quadrant and epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic atypical adipocytes and lipoblasts with hyperchromatic indented nuclei (straight arrow) and atypical spindle cells (curved arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the nuclei are positive for MDM2 (arrow). (MDM2 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a solid and cystic mass (arrow) in the posterior pancreatic body (arrowhead) without visible fat. <b>(d)</b> Fused FDG PET/CT image at the same level shows FDG avidity in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig3d.jpeg" height="1376" width="1483" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Liposarcoma in a 46-year-old man with left upper quadrant and epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic atypical adipocytes and lipoblasts with hyperchromatic indented nuclei (straight arrow) and atypical spindle cells (curved arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows that the nuclei are positive for MDM2 (arrow). (MDM2 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a solid and cystic mass (arrow) in the posterior pancreatic body (arrowhead) without visible fat. <b>(d)</b> Fused FDG PET/CT image at the same level shows FDG avidity in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig4a.jpeg" height="1456" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Liposarcoma incidentally discovered in an 87-year-old asymptomatic woman. Arterial phase CT image reformatted in the axial oblique plane using maximum intensity projection (MIP) to best demonstrate the relationship with the pancreas <b>(a)</b> and coronal contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image <b>(b)</b> show a well-circumscribed pancreatic head mass (straight arrow) containing fat attenuation (<b>*</b>) and solid areas of nodularity (curved arrow). Arrowhead = normal enhancement of the uninvolved pancreas. Note the absence of ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig4b.jpeg" height="1575" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Liposarcoma incidentally discovered in an 87-year-old asymptomatic woman. Arterial phase CT image reformatted in the axial oblique plane using maximum intensity projection (MIP) to best demonstrate the relationship with the pancreas <b>(a)</b> and coronal contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image <b>(b)</b> show a well-circumscribed pancreatic head mass (straight arrow) containing fat attenuation (<b>*</b>) and solid areas of nodularity (curved arrow). Arrowhead = normal enhancement of the uninvolved pancreas. Note the absence of ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig5a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Hyperenhancing jejunal GIST exophytically involving the posterior pancreatic tail in a 51-year-old asymptomatic woman. Transverse gray-scale US image <b>(a)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a well-circumscribed hypoechoic (straight arrow in <b>a</b>) and hyperenhancing (straight arrow in <b>b</b>) lobulated mass along the posterior margin of the distal pancreatic body/tail (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig5b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Hyperenhancing jejunal GIST exophytically involving the posterior pancreatic tail in a 51-year-old asymptomatic woman. Transverse gray-scale US image <b>(a)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a well-circumscribed hypoechoic (straight arrow in <b>a</b>) and hyperenhancing (straight arrow in <b>b</b>) lobulated mass along the posterior margin of the distal pancreatic body/tail (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig6a.jpeg" height="1325" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Large GIST involving the pancreatic head in a 76-year-old woman with weakness due to anemia. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and correlative photograph of the bisected gross specimen <b>(b)</b> show a lobular heterogeneous solid mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) with central areas of hypoattenuation (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), which correspond to areas of hemorrhage and necrosis in the gross specimen (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). Despite the large size of the mass, there is no upstream pancreatic dilatation within the normal pancreatic parenchyma (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig6b.jpeg" height="1325" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Large GIST involving the pancreatic head in a 76-year-old woman with weakness due to anemia. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and correlative photograph of the bisected gross specimen <b>(b)</b> show a lobular heterogeneous solid mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) with central areas of hypoattenuation (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), which correspond to areas of hemorrhage and necrosis in the gross specimen (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). Despite the large size of the mass, there is no upstream pancreatic dilatation within the normal pancreatic parenchyma (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig7a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. UPS in a 58-year-old man with unintentional weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the bisected gross specimen shows a white-tan multilobulated solid mass with central necrosis (∗) and focal calcification (arrow) infiltrating the duodenal wall and pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic spindle cells, many of which contain large bizarre nuclei (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal 5-mm-thick MIP image from contrast-enhanced CT shows coarse calcification (arrow) within a peripherally enhancing centrally necrotic mass in the pancreatic head (<b>*</b>), which exerts mass effect on the duodenal C-loop. Note the absence of biliary or pancreatic ductal dilation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig7b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. UPS in a 58-year-old man with unintentional weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the bisected gross specimen shows a white-tan multilobulated solid mass with central necrosis (∗) and focal calcification (arrow) infiltrating the duodenal wall and pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic spindle cells, many of which contain large bizarre nuclei (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal 5-mm-thick MIP image from contrast-enhanced CT shows coarse calcification (arrow) within a peripherally enhancing centrally necrotic mass in the pancreatic head (<b>*</b>), which exerts mass effect on the duodenal C-loop. Note the absence of biliary or pancreatic ductal dilation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig7c.jpeg" height="1200" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. UPS in a 58-year-old man with unintentional weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the bisected gross specimen shows a white-tan multilobulated solid mass with central necrosis (∗) and focal calcification (arrow) infiltrating the duodenal wall and pancreatic head. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows pleomorphic spindle cells, many of which contain large bizarre nuclei (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal 5-mm-thick MIP image from contrast-enhanced CT shows coarse calcification (arrow) within a peripherally enhancing centrally necrotic mass in the pancreatic head (<b>*</b>), which exerts mass effect on the duodenal C-loop. Note the absence of biliary or pancreatic ductal dilation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig8a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. UPS in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows relative hypoenhancement of a low-attenuation lesion in the pancreatic body (straight arrow), compared with the crescent of normally enhancing pancreas (arrowheads). Although the mass encases the superior mesenteric vein (curved arrow), there is no significant narrowing or intraluminal thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT image shows heterogeneously increased FDG uptake in the pancreatic body mass (arrow), with a maximum SUV of 17.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig8b.jpeg" height="1675" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. UPS in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows relative hypoenhancement of a low-attenuation lesion in the pancreatic body (straight arrow), compared with the crescent of normally enhancing pancreas (arrowheads). Although the mass encases the superior mesenteric vein (curved arrow), there is no significant narrowing or intraluminal thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT image shows heterogeneously increased FDG uptake in the pancreatic body mass (arrow), with a maximum SUV of 17.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig9a.jpeg" height="1331" width="1335" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Mesenchymal chondrosarcoma in a 59-year-old woman with a 2-month history of progressive jaundice, abdominal pain, and an 18-lb (8-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Radiograph from an upper gastrointestinal series shows a large densely calcified mass in the region of the pancreatic head (arrow) with associated widening of the duodenal C-loop. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a densely calcified mass enlarging the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained superior to <b>b</b> shows obstructive biliary (arrow) and pancreatic (arrowhead) ductal dilatation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen (sectioned with a bone saw) shows a large mass with a densely calcified central core (arrow) enlarging the pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig9b.jpeg" height="1577" width="1577" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Mesenchymal chondrosarcoma in a 59-year-old woman with a 2-month history of progressive jaundice, abdominal pain, and an 18-lb (8-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Radiograph from an upper gastrointestinal series shows a large densely calcified mass in the region of the pancreatic head (arrow) with associated widening of the duodenal C-loop. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a densely calcified mass enlarging the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained superior to <b>b</b> shows obstructive biliary (arrow) and pancreatic (arrowhead) ductal dilatation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen (sectioned with a bone saw) shows a large mass with a densely calcified central core (arrow) enlarging the pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig9c.jpeg" height="1577" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Mesenchymal chondrosarcoma in a 59-year-old woman with a 2-month history of progressive jaundice, abdominal pain, and an 18-lb (8-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Radiograph from an upper gastrointestinal series shows a large densely calcified mass in the region of the pancreatic head (arrow) with associated widening of the duodenal C-loop. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a densely calcified mass enlarging the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained superior to <b>b</b> shows obstructive biliary (arrow) and pancreatic (arrowhead) ductal dilatation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen (sectioned with a bone saw) shows a large mass with a densely calcified central core (arrow) enlarging the pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig9d.jpeg" height="1331" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Mesenchymal chondrosarcoma in a 59-year-old woman with a 2-month history of progressive jaundice, abdominal pain, and an 18-lb (8-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Radiograph from an upper gastrointestinal series shows a large densely calcified mass in the region of the pancreatic head (arrow) with associated widening of the duodenal C-loop. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a densely calcified mass enlarging the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained superior to <b>b</b> shows obstructive biliary (arrow) and pancreatic (arrowhead) ductal dilatation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen (sectioned with a bone saw) shows a large mass with a densely calcified central core (arrow) enlarging the pancreatic head.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig10a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Ewing sarcoma in a 37-year-old woman with several months of abdominal pain and a 10-lb (4.5-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows crowded sheets of small round blue cells. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large predominantly cystic mass with enhancing solid components (arrow) and thick septa (arrowhead) enlarging the pancreatic body.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig10b.jpeg" height="1675" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Ewing sarcoma in a 37-year-old woman with several months of abdominal pain and a 10-lb (4.5-kg) weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows crowded sheets of small round blue cells. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large predominantly cystic mass with enhancing solid components (arrow) and thick septa (arrowhead) enlarging the pancreatic body.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1204" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11b.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11c.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11d.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11e.jpeg" height="1475" width="1480" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11f.jpeg" height="1450" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig11g.jpeg" height="1475" width="1468" aria-labelledby="fig11g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11g</span>. SFT incidentally identified in a 70-year-old woman with a history of NASH (nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the cut gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed firm fleshy white-tan mass with prominent branching vessels (arrowhead) within normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows spindle cells with bland nuclei in a “patternless pattern” with abundant haphazard interstitial collagen (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows abundant positive staining for CD34. (CD34 immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×10.) MR imaging was initially performed (the patient presented for NASH cirrhosis surveillance imaging). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a well-circumscribed mass in the pancreatic head (arrow) with decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows the mass (arrow) with heterogeneous focally decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>). <b>(f, g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(f)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(g)</b> CT images show the mass with mildly increased arterial phase enhancement (arrow in <b>f</b>) relative to normal pancreas (<b>*</b>), with progressive enhancement in the portal venous phase (arrow in <b>g</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig11g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig12a.jpeg" height="1405" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. IMT in a 31-year-old man with intermittent pancreatitis and a 40-lb (18-kg) weight loss over several months. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a firm, white-tan, fleshy, infiltrative mass (straight arrow) in the head of the pancreas (arrowhead), broadly abutting the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and obstructing the common bile duct (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow) between the pancreatic head and duodenum (<b>*</b>), with abrupt obstruction of the common bile duct (curved arrow) and pancreatic duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image better shows the margins of the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow), which is hypoenhancing relative to the pancreas (arrowhead). There is mild mass effect on the duodenal lumen (<b>*</b>) without significant narrowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig12b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. IMT in a 31-year-old man with intermittent pancreatitis and a 40-lb (18-kg) weight loss over several months. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a firm, white-tan, fleshy, infiltrative mass (straight arrow) in the head of the pancreas (arrowhead), broadly abutting the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and obstructing the common bile duct (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow) between the pancreatic head and duodenum (<b>*</b>), with abrupt obstruction of the common bile duct (curved arrow) and pancreatic duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image better shows the margins of the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow), which is hypoenhancing relative to the pancreas (arrowhead). There is mild mass effect on the duodenal lumen (<b>*</b>) without significant narrowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig12c.jpeg" height="1475" width="1479" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. IMT in a 31-year-old man with intermittent pancreatitis and a 40-lb (18-kg) weight loss over several months. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a firm, white-tan, fleshy, infiltrative mass (straight arrow) in the head of the pancreas (arrowhead), broadly abutting the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and obstructing the common bile duct (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a similar orientation shows the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow) between the pancreatic head and duodenum (<b>*</b>), with abrupt obstruction of the common bile duct (curved arrow) and pancreatic duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image better shows the margins of the heterogeneous mass (straight arrow), which is hypoenhancing relative to the pancreas (arrowhead). There is mild mass effect on the duodenal lumen (<b>*</b>) without significant narrowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1480" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13c.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13d.jpeg" height="1475" width="1484" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13e.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig13e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13e</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig13f.jpeg" height="1475" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig13f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13f</span>. Large cell lymphoma in a 60-year-old woman with a 7-month history of intermittent fever, tachycardia, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a large, lobulated, fleshy, white-yellow mass in the pancreatic head, distorting the common bile duct (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large atypical lymphocytes with scant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c–e)</b> On coronal MR images, the bulky mass (straight arrow) has decreased signal intensity relative to normal pancreas (curved arrow) on the fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(c)</b>, mildly increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image <b>(d)</b>, and heterogeneous enhancement on the postcontrast fat-suppressed T1-weighted image <b>(e)</b>. Despite its large size, there is only minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead in <b>d</b> = duct in distal pancreatic body/tail) and intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>e</b>). <b>(f)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows avid uptake in the hypermetabolic tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig13f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig14a.jpeg" height="1676" width="1676" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Burkitt lymphoma in a 68-year-old woman with painless jaundice and increased belching. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and correlative fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show diffuse homogeneous enlargement of the pancreas without pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and avid FDG uptake. Although autoimmune pancreatitis can also manifest as diffuse enlargement, an absent hypoattenuating halo and marked FDG avidity favor lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig14b.jpeg" height="1676" width="1676" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Burkitt lymphoma in a 68-year-old woman with painless jaundice and increased belching. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and correlative fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show diffuse homogeneous enlargement of the pancreas without pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and avid FDG uptake. Although autoimmune pancreatitis can also manifest as diffuse enlargement, an absent hypoattenuating halo and marked FDG avidity favor lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig15a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. EMP in a 39-year-old man with no significant medical history who presented with a 20-lb (9-kg) weight loss, pruritus, and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned Whipple procedure specimen shows a mass replacing the pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead), with a gray-tan fleshy glistening periphery and a 2.5-cm-diameter red-gray center (straight arrow). A blue plastic stent is seen in the common bile duct (curved arrow). There is extrinsic compression of the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>). <b>(b–d)</b> Sequential axial contrast-enhanced CT images through the liver and pancreas show a lobulated homogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) with associated intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (curved arrow). The mass is hypoenhancing compared to the normal pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), and there is no pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig15b.jpeg" height="1548" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. EMP in a 39-year-old man with no significant medical history who presented with a 20-lb (9-kg) weight loss, pruritus, and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned Whipple procedure specimen shows a mass replacing the pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead), with a gray-tan fleshy glistening periphery and a 2.5-cm-diameter red-gray center (straight arrow). A blue plastic stent is seen in the common bile duct (curved arrow). There is extrinsic compression of the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>). <b>(b–d)</b> Sequential axial contrast-enhanced CT images through the liver and pancreas show a lobulated homogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) with associated intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (curved arrow). The mass is hypoenhancing compared to the normal pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), and there is no pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig15c.jpeg" height="1675" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. EMP in a 39-year-old man with no significant medical history who presented with a 20-lb (9-kg) weight loss, pruritus, and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned Whipple procedure specimen shows a mass replacing the pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead), with a gray-tan fleshy glistening periphery and a 2.5-cm-diameter red-gray center (straight arrow). A blue plastic stent is seen in the common bile duct (curved arrow). There is extrinsic compression of the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>). <b>(b–d)</b> Sequential axial contrast-enhanced CT images through the liver and pancreas show a lobulated homogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) with associated intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (curved arrow). The mass is hypoenhancing compared to the normal pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), and there is no pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig15d.jpeg" height="1648" width="1688" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. EMP in a 39-year-old man with no significant medical history who presented with a 20-lb (9-kg) weight loss, pruritus, and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned Whipple procedure specimen shows a mass replacing the pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead), with a gray-tan fleshy glistening periphery and a 2.5-cm-diameter red-gray center (straight arrow). A blue plastic stent is seen in the common bile duct (curved arrow). There is extrinsic compression of the second portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>). <b>(b–d)</b> Sequential axial contrast-enhanced CT images through the liver and pancreas show a lobulated homogeneous mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) with associated intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (curved arrow). The mass is hypoenhancing compared to the normal pancreatic parenchyma (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), and there is no pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig16a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. EMP in an 81-year-old woman with abdominal pain, without a prior diagnosis of myeloma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky lobulated mass diffusely and massively enlarging the pancreatic body (arrow in <b>a</b>) and tail (arrow in <b>b</b>). There is no significant biliary or pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig16b.jpeg" height="1675" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. EMP in an 81-year-old woman with abdominal pain, without a prior diagnosis of myeloma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky lobulated mass diffusely and massively enlarging the pancreatic body (arrow in <b>a</b>) and tail (arrow in <b>b</b>). There is no significant biliary or pancreatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig17a.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Plasmacytoma in a 66-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and an FDG-avid mass in the pancreatic head discovered at PET/CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (straight arrow) in the pancreatic head and body with obstructive dilatation of the distal pancreatic duct (arrowhead) and biliary ducts (curved arrow = intrahepatic bile ducts, <b>*</b> = extrahepatic bile duct). <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows robust FDG uptake throughout the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig17b.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Plasmacytoma in a 66-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and an FDG-avid mass in the pancreatic head discovered at PET/CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a homogeneous hypoenhancing mass (straight arrow) in the pancreatic head and body with obstructive dilatation of the distal pancreatic duct (arrowhead) and biliary ducts (curved arrow = intrahepatic bile ducts, <b>*</b> = extrahepatic bile duct). <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows robust FDG uptake throughout the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig18a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1204" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Paraganglioma in a 62-year-old woman with an incidentally identified pancreatic mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed homogeneous tan mass on the posterior surface of the pancreas (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows the typical <i>zellballen</i> pattern of small nests of polygonal cells with prominent nucleoli and ample granular eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm surrounded by sustentacular cells and a delicate fibrovascular network. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) Immunohistochemical stains (not shown) showed positive expression of synaptophysin and chromogranin in the polygonal cells and S100 reactivity in the sustentacular cells. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique contrast-enhanced 10-mm-thick MIP CT image shows a round well-defined mass centered in the pancreatic body with avid homogeneous enhancement (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig18b.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Paraganglioma in a 62-year-old woman with an incidentally identified pancreatic mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed homogeneous tan mass on the posterior surface of the pancreas (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows the typical <i>zellballen</i> pattern of small nests of polygonal cells with prominent nucleoli and ample granular eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm surrounded by sustentacular cells and a delicate fibrovascular network. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) Immunohistochemical stains (not shown) showed positive expression of synaptophysin and chromogranin in the polygonal cells and S100 reactivity in the sustentacular cells. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique contrast-enhanced 10-mm-thick MIP CT image shows a round well-defined mass centered in the pancreatic body with avid homogeneous enhancement (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig18c.jpeg" height="1575" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Paraganglioma in a 62-year-old woman with an incidentally identified pancreatic mass. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed homogeneous tan mass on the posterior surface of the pancreas (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows the typical <i>zellballen</i> pattern of small nests of polygonal cells with prominent nucleoli and ample granular eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm surrounded by sustentacular cells and a delicate fibrovascular network. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) Immunohistochemical stains (not shown) showed positive expression of synaptophysin and chromogranin in the polygonal cells and S100 reactivity in the sustentacular cells. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique contrast-enhanced 10-mm-thick MIP CT image shows a round well-defined mass centered in the pancreatic body with avid homogeneous enhancement (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig19a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma in a 70-year-old man 7 months after radical right nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed tan-yellow hemorrhagic mass in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-circumscribed focus of metastatic clear cell tumor (<b>*</b>) adjacent to pancreatic parenchyma <i>(P)</i> with features of chronic inflammation (intralobular and perilobular fibrosis associated with glandular atrophy). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×2.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined hyperenhancing mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) adjacent to right nephrectomy clips (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Coronal 10-mm-thick MIP image from the same data set shows multiple round hyperenhancing masses in the pancreatic head and uncinate process (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig19b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma in a 70-year-old man 7 months after radical right nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed tan-yellow hemorrhagic mass in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-circumscribed focus of metastatic clear cell tumor (<b>*</b>) adjacent to pancreatic parenchyma <i>(P)</i> with features of chronic inflammation (intralobular and perilobular fibrosis associated with glandular atrophy). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×2.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined hyperenhancing mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) adjacent to right nephrectomy clips (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Coronal 10-mm-thick MIP image from the same data set shows multiple round hyperenhancing masses in the pancreatic head and uncinate process (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig19c.jpeg" height="1473" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma in a 70-year-old man 7 months after radical right nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed tan-yellow hemorrhagic mass in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-circumscribed focus of metastatic clear cell tumor (<b>*</b>) adjacent to pancreatic parenchyma <i>(P)</i> with features of chronic inflammation (intralobular and perilobular fibrosis associated with glandular atrophy). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×2.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined hyperenhancing mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) adjacent to right nephrectomy clips (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Coronal 10-mm-thick MIP image from the same data set shows multiple round hyperenhancing masses in the pancreatic head and uncinate process (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig19d.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span>. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma in a 70-year-old man 7 months after radical right nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of the sectioned gross specimen shows a well-circumscribed tan-yellow hemorrhagic mass in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a well-circumscribed focus of metastatic clear cell tumor (<b>*</b>) adjacent to pancreatic parenchyma <i>(P)</i> with features of chronic inflammation (intralobular and perilobular fibrosis associated with glandular atrophy). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×2.) <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined hyperenhancing mass in the pancreatic head (straight arrow) adjacent to right nephrectomy clips (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Coronal 10-mm-thick MIP image from the same data set shows multiple round hyperenhancing masses in the pancreatic head and uncinate process (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170201/asset/images/large/rg.2018170201.fig20.jpeg" height="1600" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma in a 64-year-old man 19 years after radical left nephrectomy. Axial gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows round well-defined hyperenhancing masses in the pancreatic head/uncinate process (straight arrow) and lateral margin of the right kidney (curved arrow). Note medial migration of the colon into the left nephrectomy site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170201&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Manning MA, Srivastava A